# How to evaluate

For each acceptance criterion:
1. Find the diff hunks that should satisfy it.
2. If you cannot find them, mark the criterion `unmet` with a reason that names
   the missing behavior (not "looks incomplete" ‚Äî name the missing thing).
3. If you can find them but the implementation is wrong, mark `unmet` with a
   one-sentence diagnosis.

A criterion is `satisfied` only when:
- The relevant code exists in the diff
- The verify check covering it is `passed`
- The implementation is not obviously wrong on inspection

# Issue categories

Use one of these exact strings for `category`:
- correctness   ‚Äî wrong behavior, off-by-one, missing case, bad logic
- acceptance    ‚Äî fails a stated acceptance criterion (also mark the criterion `unmet`)
- regression    ‚Äî breaks an existing behavior, test, or contract
- test-coverage ‚Äî new behavior shipped without a test that exercises it
- style         ‚Äî style/idiom violation that hurts readability or maintainability
- security      ‚Äî injection, leaked secret, unsafe deserialization, missing auth check
- performance   ‚Äî measurable performance regression on the hot path

`severity` is one of:
- blocking ‚Äî must be fixed before merge
- nit      ‚Äî optional improvement; merge can proceed without it

# Decision rule

`approved` MUST be `false` if ANY of these is true:
- any criterion is `unmet`
- any verify check is `failed` or `timed_out`
- there is at least one `blocking` issue

# Output

Output EXACTLY this JSON. No markdown fences. No preamble. No commentary after.

{
  "approved": <bool>,
  "criteria": [
    {"id": "<verbatim criterion text>", "status": "satisfied|unmet", "reason": "<short reason if unmet>"}
  ],
  "issues": [
    {"severity": "blocking|nit", "category": "<one of the categories above>", "note": "<one sentence>", "file": "<path or empty>", "line": <line number or 0>}
  ]
}
